I don't trust Putin, so I presume his agreement to meet Biden doesn't mean anything.  But I'm raising no from 3% to 6% because each day that goes by without an attack is slight evidence of a bluff, especially now that the olympics are over.  Plus, Putin could be enticed to change his mind on invading even if he is not trustworthy. An invasion could start at any time, however-- please don't misunderstand me.  See, for example, this Tweet, which I saw while writing this post: "David Martin of 
@CBSNews, a superb reporter I’ve known for decades and worked with at the original Newsweek for many years—and whom I trust totally—says #Putin has just ordered  #Russian forces to invade #Ukraine in its entirety, with reserve units following to run an occupation."
https://twitter.com/howardfineman/status/1495563857280081920

I believe the invasion is coming, most likely within the coming month, and perhaps as early as within the coming week. I believe it's going to happen for several reasons, the exact combination of which only Putin knows. I believe it'll happen because:
* Putin wants to rebuild the Russian empire;
* Putin is getting older and wants to have a lasting legacy; 
* Putin thinks the Soviet Union should never have been disbanded; 
* Putin believes that some or all of Ukraine is rightfully part of Russia; 
* Putin wants to control a buffer zone between Russia and NATO countries;
* Putin is concerned that NATO weapons will increasingly be placed in countries adjacent to Russia; 
* Putin specifically doesn't want short-range and medium-range missiles in Ukraine (even though he has nuclear weapons and nuclear-capable Iskander missiles in Kaliningrad, and may soon put nuclear missiles in Belarus) and thinks that he must act now or it will soon be too late;
* Putin wants a Russian sphere of influence between Russia and NATO countries, and he doesn't want a pro-Western state in Ukraine because he feels it undermines Russia;
* Putin doesn't want any former Soviet republic ever again to have a close relationship with NATO (i.e., membership or the placement of NATO weapons or advisors), and so Ukraine will serve as an example of what happens if one gets too close;
* Putin feels threatened by having a democracy in Ukraine and doesn't want it to exist as an example; 
* Putin doesn't want to lose control of Donbas;
* Putin thinks the time is right because Europe is dependent on Russian gas, and the US is embroiled in internal controversies;
* Putin thinks the time is right because he recently (~18 months ago) got control over Belarus and now has a launching pad for a northern invasion, and he has been practicing and gearing up for an invasion ever since;
* Putin wants to weaken European and N American cohesion, both within and between countries; and
* Putin thinks his goals in Ukraine are achievable and will incur minimal military costs.
I'm sure some of these are more important than others, and I'm sure I've missed some. Almost everything is in place militarily, down to the very last details. Russia has the smallest force contingent deployed in is eastern regions in decades, as the vast majority of its military resources are concentrated around Ukraine. We know of a planned false flag operation, plans for a staged video, an impossible set of demands for NATO countries, attempts to recruit members of the Ukraine Parliament to hand the government over to Russia upon invasion, and a complete plan for installing a puppet government. The Russian people are being told that the US and the West are pushing Russia into war, and that most of the eastern half of Ukraine is historically part of Russia. Disinformation and cyberattacks are ramped up. I'm not sure what will happen after Russian forces invade Ukraine. I'm sure that Putin's goal is to install a puppet government in Kyiv and for Russian forces eventually to withdraw once the situation is stable. I'm not completely sure which direction(s) the invasion will come from first. Probably Donbas and/or Crimea, followed by a push to take the entire southeast from Odesa to Kharkiv. It will all probably start with aerial bombardments. I believe many here (and elsewhere) think that Russia won't invade Ukraine because the costs will be too high, both militarily and financially, and for other reasons. I agree that the costs will be enormous. But such costs haven't stopped previous aggressors, and I don't think they'll stop Putin. Moreover, Putin may well underestimate the military costs, much like the US underestimated the military costs of the Iraqi invasion and how difficult it would be to achieve its goals there. I think what's about to happen is incredibly sad and tragic. People will suffer. It makes me very sad to think about. As always, I hope I am wrong. Later edit: interesting assessment of the military buildup: http://blog.vantagepointnorth.net/2022/01/russian-buildup-critical-elements-point.html?m=1

